headline: What Wall Street Thought of Today’s Powell Speech
summary: Wall Street traders dialed up bets on rate cuts Friday and tamped down their expectations of future volatility.  Futures pricing Friday suggested traders saw a roughly 83% chance that the Fed will cut rates at its next meeting, according to CME Group data, up from 75% Thursday.  “The Fed isn’t going to be the party-pooper,” said Brian Jacobsen, chief economist at Annex Wealth Management.

headline: Powell Remarks Boost Rate-Cut Bets
summary: Wall Street traders are dialing up bets on interest-rate cuts after Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell opened the door to a cut as soon as next month.  Futures pricing Friday morning suggested traders saw a 91% chance that the Fed will cut rates at its next meeting, according to CME Group data, up from 75% Thursday.

headline: TSX climbs to record high as Powell leaves rate-cut option on the table
summary: Canada's main index jumped over 1% to hit a record high on Friday, led by technology and energy shares, after U.S. Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell signalled willingness towards future rate cuts at the Jackson Hole Symposium.  At 10:35 a.m. ET (1435 GMT), the Toronto Stock Exchange's S&P/TSX composite index was up 1.02% at 28,341.66 points, surpassing the intra-day record high of August 13.  Powell on Friday pointed to a possible rate cut at the central bank's September meeting but stopped short of committing, in remarks that walked a narrow line acknowledging growing risks to the job market while also indicating risks of higher inflation remain.
